UN chief says there are no military solutions in Syria
Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon says his response to Russia's military support for Syria is that "there is no military solution" to the nearly five-year conflict and more weapons would only worsen the violence and suffering of millions.
The UN chief again called on all parties, including the divided UN Security Council, to unite and support negotiations to find a political solution.
Ban told a conference on Wednesday that he plans to meet this month with the foreign ministers of the five permanent council members - the United States, Russia, China, Britain and France - on the sidelines of the General Assembly's ministerial session to discuss Syria.
Ban expressed regret that divisions within the council and between the Syrian people and regional powers "have made this situation unresolvable".
Ban urged the five permanent members to show the solidarity and unity they had shown when they succeeded in reaching an agreement on Iran's nuclear weapons, thereby addressing the crisis in Syria.
Eight poll numbers that show Donald Trump has a real shot.
Some have tried to label him a "flip-flop" politician.
Others called it a joke.
And others are waiting for the implosion.
But no matter how some Republicans try to knock Donald Trump off the top of the polls, it hasn't worked (yet).
Ten of the last 11 national polls have shown Donald Trump leading by double-digit percentages, and some voices are beginning to seriously question what this means for the real estate mogul's nomination chances.
Of course, it's still early days.
None of this says that Trump will win the race for the Republican nomination.
Pundits point out that at the same time in 2011, Rick Perry's lead gave way to Herman Cain in the polls, but neither won a state in the nomination race.
And the reasons why he would fight hard in the general election are numerous.
But outside groups like Jeb Bush's Super PAC and the economic conservative group the Club for Growth are recognizing Trump's power and starting to support him with money.
Here are some numbers from recent surveys that suggest the real estate mogul is not just a fluke:
The numbers indicating support for Trump have turned 180 degrees.
Just before Donald Trump announced his candidacy in mid-June, a Monmouth University poll showed that only two in 10 Republicans had a positive view of the real estate mogul.
By mid-July, the figure had climbed to 40 percent.
At the beginning of August, it was 52%.
Currently, six out of 10 Republicans have a favorable opinion of Donald Trump.
About three in 10 say they have a negative view.
These figures hold.
A Quinnipiac poll last week in Iowa concluded that 60 percent of Republicans in the region have a favorable view of Trump.
Two-thirds of GOP voters would be happy if Trump won the nomination race.
In a CNN/ORC poll last week, 67% of Republicans said they would be "excited" or "thrilled" if Trump won the nomination.
Only two in 10 say they would be "upset" if Trump won the nomination race.
Only Ben Carson generates about the same level of enthusiasm as Trump (43% say they would be "enthusiastic" versus 40% who say the same about Trump).
The closest in terms of enthusiasm?
Marco Rubio, with only 21%.
On the other hand, 47% of Republican voters say they would be "displeased" or "angry" if front-runner Jeb Bush wins the nomination race.
Most Republicans don't see Trump's temper as an issue.
Although Donald Trump has been heavily criticized for his insults and bombastic style, 52 percent of Republican voters nationwide believe the real estate mogul has the right temperament to be president, according to an ABC News/Washington Post poll conducted Monday.
We see the same numbers in Iowa, where 52 percent of Republicans think Trump has the right personality to lead, according to a Quinnipiac poll last week.
However, 44% believe he lacks the personality to act effectively and nearly six in 10 independents say his temperament has no place in the White House, according to ABC/Post.
Republican voters are getting used to the idea.
When they take the intellectual stance, Republican voters think Trump is authentic.
According to a CNN/ORC poll conducted last week, when asked who was most likely to win the race for the GOP nomination, four in 10 said Trump.
That's a far cry from late July, when four in 10 would have bet on Jeb Bush.
Full disclosure: in the past, GOP voters haven't been very good at reading the future.
At the same time in the last election, four out of 10 Republicans chose Rick Perry in the race for the nomination, versus only 28 percent for Mitt Romney.
But these numbers show that a majority of GOP voters see Trump's campaign as credible.
Even though the Republicans have retreated to another candidate, Trump is still leading them all.
Some voices say the divided situation will likely contribute to Trump's victory, while support against Trump will split into more than a dozen candidates.
But a Monmouth University poll in early September found that in the hypothetical scenario of Trump working with most of the other Republican candidates, Trump would almost always have majority support.
Trump is 13 points behind Carly Fiorina, 14 points behind Marco Rubio, 15 points behind Walker, 19 points behind Jeb Bush, and finally 33 points behind Rand Paul, John Kasich, and Chris Christie.
He's neck and neck with Ted Cruz.
The only candidate to beat him?
Ben Carson would beat the businessman by 19 points in a hypothetical one-on-one matchup.
Most of Donald Trump's supporters say they have made up their minds.
A new CBS/NYT poll released Tuesday shows that more than half of Trump voters say they won't change their vote.
Obviously, a lot can happen in this regard and no one can say that they will never change their minds.
46% say they are open to changing their mind.
However, Trump's most prominent opponent is currently neurosurgeon Ben Carson, but he is twice as likely as voters who say they have decided to vote for Trump.
Six out of 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
Ever since Donald Trump called immigrants from Mexico "rapists" in his campaign kickoff speech two months ago, immigration has been a central issue in the 2016 campaign.
Some are concerned that Trump's bombastic style will drive a wedge between key Hispanic voters and the Republican Party and hurt rebranding efforts.
But according to an ABC/Post poll released Monday, six in 10 Republicans say they agree with Trump on immigration.
So it seems that as long as immigration remains in the spotlight, so will Donald Trump.
Frustration with authority reaches new heights.
Donald Trump and Ben Carson are now supported by almost half of Republican voters, largely because of their outsider status.
According to an ABC/Post poll released Monday, six out of 10 Republicans say they prefer a political outsider to someone with government experience.
People are also angry at the authorities in Washington.
