Jeremy Corbyn makes his debut on Prime Minister's Questions
Since his election, Mr Corbyn's debut at the PMQs has been long-awaited
The new leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn, will later make his Prime Minister's Questions debut, facing David Cameron for the first time.
Mr Corbyn will address the first of his six questions shortly after lunch; his performance is likely to be closely scrutinised by the media and Labour MPs.
In his weekly appearances, he called for "less theater and more facts".
He also stated that he might give up some of his holdings and give them to his colleagues.
The showdown will be Mr Corbyn's first parliamentary test as leader, coming after he appointed a "shadow cabinet" and delivered a speech to the TUC's annual conference on Tuesday.
Meanwhile, the Labour leader's decision to remain silent during the national anthem at a service on Tuesday to mark the 75th anniversary of the Battle of Britain drew criticism from some Conservative MPs and made headlines.
Mr Corbyn's decision not to sing the national anthem drew attention
A spokesman for Mr Corbyn said he had "respectfully remained silent" and acknowledged the "heroism of the RAF in the Battle of Britain".
But a member of Mr Corbyn's shadow cabinet, Owen Smith, told the BBC's Two's Newsnight programme that he would have advised the Labour leader to sing the national anthem "regardless" of his belief that the monarchy should be abolished.
Around a dozen ministers in the shadow cabinet refused to be part of Mr Corbyn's leadership team, citing differences of opinion over the economy, defence and foreign affairs, while less than a sixth of the parliamentary party supported him as leader.
The BBC's political correspondent Robin Brant says policy differences are "piling up" in the Labour Party after Mr Corbyn's appointment over his stance on the European Union and the benefits cap.
Mr Corbyn told the TUC conference that Labour would bring in changes that would remove the idea of capping altogether.
A few hours later, Mr Smith, the Work and Pensions Secretary, said the party was "very clear" in its exclusive opposition to the government's plans to reduce the cap from £26,000 to £23,000.
Mr Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron in the gallery in the last decade, since he took over the leadership of the Conservative Party.
The Labour leader, who has promised a different approach to politics, says he has ideas "from outside sources" for questions to ask Mr Cameron and has received over 30,000 suggestions.
The Islington North MP said the PMQs were too confrontational and that he would refrain from retorts and attacks, pledging instead to focus on serious issues such as poverty, inequality and the challenges facing young people.
Mr Corbyn has stated that Angela Eagle, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, will take his place at PMQs when he cannot attend - for example when Mr Cameron travels abroad.
He also expressed the idea that he would allow other colleagues to speak occasionally, saying that he had approached the Speaker of the House of Commons, John Bercow, to discuss the matter.
In 2005, when he took over the leadership, Mr Cameron said he wanted to move away from the 'Punch and Judy' style of politics often associated with PMQs but admitted a few years later that he had not succeeded in doing so.
Since its first broadcast in 1990, PMQs have been considered a key barometer of a leader's reasoning, the way he or she leads the Chamber of Deputies, and his or her standing among fellow parliamentarians, although critics say it has become a caricature and is in need of deep reform.
