Here's what happens when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates.
Interest rates will rise and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise and the economy will go into recession.
That's what we know.
What we don't know is when it will happen and how long it will last.
In economics, history offers few clues as to the time frame.
After the first interest rate increase, the recession occurred in only 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor of how the economy and financial assets responded.
That's why Fed officials have emphasized so strongly that investors should focus not on when interest rates start to rise but on the trajectory of how long it will take to normalize.
Indeed, there are multiple variables at play.
However, in the end, market participants may find that all the hype about interest rate increases has been exaggerated.
"The Fed's first interest rate hike since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a sign of the era of cheap money", Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels to constitute the seismic shock that everyone seems to fear.
But that's not to say there won't be effects.
Here's how some sectors of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation the market has faced in recent months, the anticipation of an interest rate hike may make things volatile for a while.
But at the moment of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
"There seems to be a tendency for returns to capital to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first increase, perhaps again reflecting the lag in monetary policy", Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what happens after Fed hikes.
Specifically, over the past 35 years, the market has risen sharply - by about 14 percent - moving towards rising interest rates, fairly unchanged in the 250-day period afterwards (average rise of 2.6 percent) after which it returns to normal after 500 days, with an average return over the last six cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis published on Barron's by the chief strategist of Nuveen Asset Management.
Deutsche stated that the impact on equities tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate cycle and the benefits start to decline.
Recession is a fact of economic life but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that have not existed before that could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, gross domestic product will approach its historic low point for a Fed interest rate increase.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice was nominal GDP below 4,5%.
Even though in the second quarter of 2015 the value was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Raising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and raise the question "whether this time is different", Deutsche said.
Market participants have been preparing all year for a Fed rate hike decision, with all eyes on this week's Federal Open Market Committee meeting, which ends on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an interest rate hike at this meeting, forward trading indicates a probability of only 25%.
"In our study after 1950, all cycles of interest rate increases to date have been in a profit growth supercycle, with GDP eclipsing pre-recession peaks very quickly after recovery began", the report stated.
On the contrary, it was a strangely slow recovery from the worst recession of the period considered.
The current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has expected since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and it has reached 74 months and counting.
Fixed income has also been volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster for bonds than for equities when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, the benefits seem to change direction as soon as the first rise/fall in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate cycle, bond yields fall immediately,' Deutsche said.
Charles Schwab strategists believe that these interest rate increases will cause short-term and long-term bond yields to converge, flattening the curve.
High-yield bonds do better in such an environment, though "we're still cautious about pushing yield", Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab, said in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that markets have already adjusted to expectations of Fed policy.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the projected decline in inflation, there are some signs that the market has adjusted to the prospect of tighter monetary policy", Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is straighter, the average credit spread has widened and volatility has increased -- all characteristics of the market when the Fed tightens policy.
Overall, US-based companies will benefit from higher interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
Heavily indebted multinationals will suffer because a rising dollar will make their products more expensive in the global marketplace and their debt more expensive.
"History shows that 'quality' stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months following an initial interest rate hike", the Goldman Sachs analyst said in a report to clients.
Firms with strong balance sheets outperformed those with weak balance sheets after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with both high returns on equity and low volatility stocks also outperformed their lower quality peers by an average of 4 percentage points and 3 percentage points, respectively.
Debt will become a major issue.
Companies with a high percentage of floating debt have the most to lose, Goldman says.
Consumers will also benefit from the rise in the dollar.
Savers could also benefit, although experts disagree on how quickly this will happen.
