Advantages and disadvantages of converting credits into Swiss francs
Two offers for the conversion of Swiss franc loans into lei have already appeared on the banking market, the main advantages being the absence of currency risk and lower rates.
The downside may come a few years down the road, when the variable interest rate can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process of converting Volksbank's loans into francs and Bancpost has announced the conversion offer for its own customers.
According to data compiled by analysts of the financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers a three-year fixed interest rate in lei of 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, Bancă Transilvania's conversion offer was accepted by 83% of clients with loans in RON due to two successive reductions: the balance was reduced by the amount of risk and administration fees paid by the client, then an additional 22,5% reduction was applied to the RON balance.
Both offers reduce the rates of their customers, compared to what they paid monthly equivalent in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42,5% and Bancpost by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Benefits
The main advantage of converting CHF loans into lei is that the currency risk is eliminated, the consumer is protected against future increases in the franc and the loan will be repaid in the currency of his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no revaluation of the property, no additional collateral and no further proof of income is required.
In practice, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the loan and no additional costs as in the case of refinancing.
Also, both banks offer a discount on the monthly rate, compared to what customers were paying before the conversion, equivalent in lei.
The risks
The problem is that the first few years are mostly interest, and the customer pays very little in principal.
Bancpost's offer of very low interest for the first three years seems advantageous to customers.
However, it is not known how this interest rate will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be higher than 3,25%, so overall the cost reduction is also lower.
A possible risk for all RON floating rate loans is that ROBOR will increase significantly in the coming years (more than Libor - CHF).
For example, the three-month ROBOR is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached 6%, in 2009 it was over 15%, and in a few days in 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, other costs, not mentioned in the initial offer, may arise.
