Violinist David Grimal: In Bach's time there were no world tours.
Beethoven, Brahms, Bartok, Enescu were working people, artists and not salesmen.
The French violinist David Grimal is one of the great artists of our time, known not only as a soloist but also as the initiator of an unusual project, quite "strange", as he himself says, Les Dissonances - an orchestra made up of international soloists and talented musicians, who perform a symphonic repertoire without a conductor, and that makes it at least a curiosity in the classical music landscape.
Les Dissonances was this year at the Enescu Festival with two performances: a performance on Sunday, in which the soloist was David Grimal, the founder of the orchestra, and one on Monday, when the cellist Xavier Phillips was in the foreground, the works composed by Enescu being unavoidable.
Both performances, held on the stage of the Athenaeum, showed the audience another way of interpreting classical music.
Les Dissonances appeared on the music scene in 2004 being, at that time, the only classical music ensemble without a conductor.
The conductor is the most important musician for musicians.
It's true, on the one hand musicians need an education to become either soloists or performers in an orchestra -- I'm talking about instrumentalists, not composers.
They are trained as "skilled workers".
They themselves feel they need a conductor.
On the other side of the stage, for the audience, all the musical fetishization is focused on the conductor.
And so the business, the music business, is marketing itself.
So we're not talking about music anymore.
So if you look at this world, you have a skilled workforce, which is stupid, and an audience that can't listen but has to watch, which is stupid".
The violinist attributes this change in his playing to the "musical disappointments" of his solo career.
I was like a high-level athlete who had to do the same exercise all over the world with different orchestras, to make a lot of money and bring money to the music industry.
Ten years ago, when I was in my mid-30s, I found this very depressing, because I could no longer find creativity and human brotherhood in this system.
So I found no sense in continuing on this path.
So I decided to create Les Dissonances.
This was in 2004, and at that time nobody did this without a conductor: "The music world, extremely conservative, did not want such projects".
"How can you imagine doing marketing with a collective of musicians in which there is no ego?" asks the artist.
David Grimal admits that Les Dissonaces is "a luxury", stating that none of the musicians who make up the orchestra depend on the success of this project for a living.
In the 10 years of the ensemble's existence, the lack of a conductor has not proved to be a hindrance in the musical act: "Curiously, the more complex the repertoire, the simpler it seems, because all the musicians are obliged to be present in the opera and not just in the role", says Grimal, adding that at Sunday's performance "there were 74 conductors on stage".
In Grimal's opinion, the Enescu Festival is a "very courageous" one, precisely because he also invited Les Dissonances: "An extraordinary festival, where the greatest orchestras in the world are present and play 3 times a day, and in the middle of these orchestras you have invited this strange group".
In a temple of orchestral tradition like the Enescu Festival, there is room and interest for something different, something that breaks down barriers.
