In the most anticipated meeting in years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide whether it's time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank's meeting room, a mural of the United States will loom.
The map is meant as a reminder that Janet L. Yellen, the Fed Chair, and her colleagues must put the nation's economic interests above all else.
The Federal Reserve was given a dual task by Congress: to maximize employment in the US and to maintain price stability.
But since the Great Depression, Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third burden could be the X factor in a hard-to-predict decision that will be announced on Tuesday about whether the U.S. economy is ready to be unburdened by the unprecedented stimulus provided by the near-zero short-term interest rate that has been in place since late 2008.
Even if most data point to a strongly growing economy, the recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials from adding to the volatility by raising the federal funds rate - even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
"Obviously, the labor market and inflation are going to be the first and foremost things they're going to look at", said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
'But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise interest rates, the growing uncertainty in the world market is enough to give them reason to wait,' she said.
There is no consensus on what decision the Fed will take, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of the economists surveyed recently by Bloomberg anticipated an interest rate hike this week.
But financial markets are expecting the Fed to delay, with a key indicator showing the probability of an increase at just 30%.
This would indicate a stock market decline if the Fed raises interest rates, unless policymakers soften the blow by promising that it would be a long time before the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The rally was triggered by expectations that Fed policymakers will keep interest rates steady this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
"It would be surprising if the Fed were to raise interest rates at this time", Lonski said.
If Fed policymakers were to do so, "they would have to act profoundly in their policies to avoid panic in financial markets".
Other experts said that an interest rate hike would calm financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be on track to raise rates by 0.25% this month, the first small step toward the slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen stated in the spring and early summer that she expected an interest rate increase this year despite objections raised by liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth has been solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1 percent last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers total employment.
Wage earnings showed signs of improvement.
And although inflation continued to fall short of the central bank's annual target, Fed policymakers said a key reason was the temporary effect of plummeting oil prices.
The economy "can and needs higher rates given the tight labor market", said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to go into a tailspin later that month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 16% below its record high reached in May as investors feared that China's slowing economy would drag down global growth.
The market has retreated somewhat this month, with the Dow now about 10% below its May high.
For Fed policymakers, market turmoil adds to the complex calculation of the timing of interest rate increases.
"Without what's happened in the financial markets and the news about the weakening Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would be firmer in the meeting", said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior fellow at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Fed official.
Now, he predicts they'll wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
"There's a lot of uncertainty about what the impact is going to be on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data to rely on after the events in China", Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed's major interests, so it should practically not be factored into its decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the world's monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank's influence has been huge.
The mere hint by then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed might "taper" its monetary expansion sent shockwaves through global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the global economy.
Its decision-making process is "more art than science", said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at wealth management firm Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that "The Fed has a history of overreacting to changes in financial markets that seem unrelated to economic fundamentals".
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee, the decision-making body that supported the rate hike, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis affecting Asia led the Fed to cut its benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, "despite implications with limited identifiability for US growth", Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reversed those declines.
The Fed should only put the issue of financial stability first in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England's interest rate-setting committee.
The recent turmoil is nowhere near that level, he said.
"We certainly don't want to get into a situation where we fear an interest rate hike because markets are upset", said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the dual mandate and doesn't mention financial stability, and until something changes in that regard, I don't think they should take premature action.
