Weight-loss surgery may be useful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight-loss surgery in mildly obese people with type 2 diabetes could be maintained for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still too early to say whether mildly obese diabetics live longer after weight-loss surgery than those who undergo nonsurgical treatments.
"It takes a long time to centralize mortality data", said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an obesity surgeon who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight-loss surgery, also called bariatric surgery, uses various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been shown to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in morbidly obese people with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or greater.
BMI, a measure of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range 18.5-24.9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people who had surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI of people who received nonsurgical treatments for diabetes remained almost the same at 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured in 36 percent and partially cured in 28 percent.
In the medical group, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1 percent and partially cured in only 2 percent of subjects.
In addition, control of blood pressure, triglycerides, and "bad" LDL cholesterol "was generally better in the surgery group", the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal hemoglobin A1c level is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean haemoglobin A1c level decreased from approximately 9% to approximately 6%.
But in the medical group, it stayed at about eight percent.
But this improved "glycemic control" - reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels - did not reduce five-year mortality, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average outcomes associated with the two types of surgery.
At five years, compared with the sleeve gastrectomy group, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), had greater decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%) and were more likely to have complete remission from diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of obese people in Sweden that surgery extends life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona College of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die after 15 years, compared to a group who tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic outlook for people with BMIs under 35 interested in the procedure.
"This is where this paper is critical, because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group", without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when the patient's BMI reaches 27-30.
"I think we're waiting too long to urge people to take this seriously", she said.
I think once they've accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it's extremely difficult to get back to normal.
