Four-fold increase in the number of children ingesting hand sanitizer in the past 4 years
According to the Georgia Poison Control Center, U.S. poison control centers have reported a roughly 400 percent increase since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who have swallowed high-alcohol hand sanitizer.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Poison Control Center, reports of children under 12 ingesting hand sanitizer increased from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
"Children have more frequent access to these products and unfortunately a percentage of them end up in the emergency room", Lopez told CNN.
Lopez stated that some children intentionally drink detergent and others do it to impress their friends or to respond to challenges on social media.
On YouTube, you can watch videos of teenagers drinking detergent to create cheap drinks.
Apparently, the teens mixed the mouthwash with alcohol to make a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted by the attractive smell of detergent.
"A child doesn't think it's hurting them", says Lopez.
Many of the most attractive types are scented.
Strawberry, grape, orange-flavored hand sanitizers are the most appealing to children.
The hand sanitizer contains approximately 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, just a few sips can cause alcohol poisoning.
"It's highly concentrated alcohol", Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the poison control center at the University of Kansas Hospital, told Fox 4 in Kansas City.
So we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand sanitizers in accessible places, and if kids can get to them, that's a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four sprays of strawberry-flavored hand sanitizer at school, ended up in the emergency room for treatment.
She had a blood alcohol level of 179, twice the threshold at which an adult is legally considered intoxicated, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room physician who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was stuttering and unable to walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight at a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain damage, as the girl fell and hit her head from the alcohol, Ritchey said.
"It was scary", Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah's mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free products or wet wipes and to keep hand sanitizer out of children's reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing hand sanitizer that contained an undeclared toxic ingredient.
The health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, specified as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth-graders in upstate New York plotted to poison their "evil" teacher by "putting antibacterial products in the classroom", according to a police report.
The teacher is highly allergic to hand sanitizer and has banned it from her classroom.
The police considered the plan "insignificant" and referred the disciplinary matter to the school inspectorate.
