The absence of similar characters in the series is evident, given that the need for men to open up is now more desperate than ever, with suicide rates among young men reaching a 15-year high.
In 2013, suicide was the leading cause of death for men aged 20-45 in the UK, and remains three times more common in men than women.
In an attempt to address the issue, the Campaign Against Living Miserably (CALM) designated 2015 as the Year of the Man, wanting to challenge the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it.
Friendship is at the heart of the struggle to meet this challenge.
A recent study of more than 2,000 high school students with symptoms of depression concluded that if the sufferer is surrounded by enough "healthy mood" friends, his chances of recovery double.
Similarly, for people who aren't depressed, having a circle of mentally healthy friends cuts the likelihood of developing a mental disorder in half.
Of course, for friendship to be effective, it must first be available.
In this era of social media-dominated communication, where the emphasis is on style over substance, the immediacy of response often takes precedence over meaningful contact.
Our digital lives have doubled down on the need to create the appearance of a strong, fun-loving, successful personality, even when in reality it's isolation that dominates.
This superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values; money, image, social status, all at the expense of intrinsic values -- our inner desire for personal growth and friendship -- which affects our mental health even more deeply.
The billionaire inventor of a video game recently explained that money really does not buy happiness.
The beauty of Friends was that it brought attention to this idea.
Characters were not defined by their job but by their own personality, which they showed by interacting as friends.
The humor of Joey and Chandler's frequent hugs, their moments of watching football in their comfy armchairs, and Ross' passion for Rachel came from knowing that men can relate to this situation, even if they often shy away from fully exploring their feelings.
As one social worker explained to me, "My role in listening to suicidal and depressed people showed me how even the smallest interactions with friends can make a difference".
Often, people who come to us don't feel able to talk to their friends.
The old adage of going it alone is powerful, as is the feeling of being perceived as weak if you talk openly about your problems.
Friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer more long-term psychological coping mechanisms.
The show highlighted the small moments of male friendship.
As much as objective, out-of-the-box intervention over the phone helps people in moments of despair, long-term support comes from family and close friends.
So if you're attending Comedy Central's FriendsFest this weekend, with a full set replay to celebrate, why not invite your friends over for coffee at Central Perk.
Or better yet, if you see someone alone at Starbucks, smile and say hello.
You never know what a difference your friendship could make.
