The government approved on Wednesday the "National Strategy on Immigration for the period 2015-2018" and the "Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage that Romania is going through in its efforts to modernize the process of managing immigration on national territory", according to a press release.
The source quoted shows that the strategy aims at managing the phenomenon of immigration effectively, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and lines of action reflecting policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems encountered by the States in Romania's immediate neighbourhood, measures are envisaged for the unitary and coherent management of situations arising from a possible inflow of illegal immigrants into the territory of Romania, generated by crisis situations of a political, social, economic or military nature.
'The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time they will pay special attention to citizens coming from countries with migration potential or who may pose a threat to national security,' adds the same source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that may influence immigration and asylum, including the continuation of the conflict situation in Syria, the reactivation of the conflict in Iraq, the continuation of an unstable situation in the areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), the continuation and intensification of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets out some general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more stringent checks on the legality of the stay of third-country nationals on Romanian territory and the proper application of removal and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also contain specific objectives relevant for the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the Romanian territory for third-country nationals who meet employment needs, promoting access for third-country nationals to Romanian higher education institutions for fields and professions identified as lacking.
As regards the 2015 Action Plan, the Government considers that it is 'a means of setting out concrete activities leading to the creation of a flexible system to tackle the growing migration phenomenon'.
