In the refugee crisis, Romania has so far acted like a small country.
It's a legitimate strategy, but then you can't ask to be treated like a seventh EU country.
Large countries come up with solutions for the whole EU, says Cristian Ghinea, board member of the Romanian Centre for European Policy.
In an interview with Ziare.com, Cristian Ghinea pointed out that Europe cannot be turned into a fortress and that purely police methods will not work in this crisis: "Perhaps we have doubts about the quality of the values these people bring".
But there are masses that have been set in motion and we can't reverse history.
Migration is a reality to which we need to adapt as best we can and make them adapt to us.
According to Cristian Ghinea, we are in an extremely emotional moment, when politicians feel the need to show their muscles.
After it passes, Europeans will not be willing to give up free movement, but the rules in the Schengen area must be changed: "Schengen is now like an animal created in another era and which was not adapted to today's situation".
Where are we on the refugee crisis after this JHA council that actually solved nothing?
It is clear that the EC President in agreement with Donald Tusk did not want to force a vote in the Council.
All the polls said he'd get the votes.
Before the Lisbon Treaty, the principle of unanimity applied in JHA and any Member State could block any decision.
That is why there has been very little integration in the area of justice and home affairs.
After Lisbon, the normal procedure applies, whereby the Commission takes the initiative and the Council approves it with the vote of 55% of the Member States, i.e. 16, representing 65% of the EU population.
The calculations said the votes were there.
But they didn't want to go forward.
Because it's such a sensitive issue, there was a backlash even in Germany against Chancellor Merkel's open-door policy, and they didn't want it to come across in many countries as "the EU is sending us migrants".
So they postponed, but the problem remains because obviously this wave is creating a huge problem for Schengen governance and we're probably going to see big changes there in the coming period.
So the mandatory quotas weren't really eliminated, but the subject was just left to cool?
Yes, on the other hand, there is talk of a greater involvement of the Frontex agency in the management of external borders, which means a shift from the individual responsibility of Member States at the Schengen external border to the responsibility of Community agencies.
Greece's border with Turkey is also Germany's border with Turkey, de facto, and this wave of migration has stretched the limits of the old Schengen system.
Maybe the Dublin principle, where migrants are the responsibility of the first country they enter, will be abandoned, because it's not sustainable.
If Greece collapses, you can't keep saying it's Greece's business.
It's a common problem.
Precisely because the problem is common, is it possible to solve it without a precise, perhaps even mandatory, mechanism for sharing the effort of reception?
Nobody knows exactly how mandatory quotas will work, if at all.
Because one problem remains: what do you do with a man who doesn't want to come to Romania or Portugal, but to Sweden or Germany?
I don't think European countries are going to start picking up migrants: you go to country X or country Y.
It will probably lead to single filtering centres in Greece or Turkey where asylum applications will be processed.
They're working on solutions like this.
But the problem doesn't have a simple solution.
There are countries that have decades of experience in trying to integrate migrants, there are countries without any experience, like Romania, where the problem of migrants will increase the xenophobic current.
The fact is that we're talking about millions of people who are in Turkey, in Lebanon, in Jordan, who are living in precarious camps and who have just started to go to Europe.
One estimate is that only 10% have left, the Mediterranean is hard to cross in winter, but we expect an even bigger wave next year.
What do we do with these people?
My prediction is that we'll get used to this problem, we won't look at it so catastrophically from a media point of view.
You were talking about countries with more or less experience.
Do you think there is any place that has really succeeded in integrating large groups from a non-European culture?
I look at the Maghreb in France, the Turks in Germany, they're all enclaved.
I wouldn't go in for radical statements.
Of course, integrating them is more difficult than with other waves of migration, but that doesn't mean they don't integrate at all.
There's a disconnected part that's creating major social problems in France, in Germany, in Britain.
But purely police means won't work.
Fortress Europe is an illusion.
The mechanisms of integration into European societies need to be examined.
There have been some mistakes here.
We have to be more sophisticated.
Let's ask these people to learn the language, to try to take on the values, not to stay with one foot in Europe and one in their home country, bringing the rest of their family including through marriages of convenience.
But you have to separate the immediate problem of these people from the long-term problem of integrating them.
Just because others have failed to integrate in the long term doesn't mean we have to watch them drown in the Mediterranean.
Maybe we have doubts about the quality of the values that these people bring.
And if there's going to be an intervention in Syria, which I don't believe, it doesn't mean it's going to rebuild the country overnight and you can take them back.
Until solutions emerge, we see fortresses within Europe.
Borders are being closed, walls are being built, border controls are being reintroduced in the Schengen area.
Is the European project in danger?
The European project as such did not, the Schengen area as it was constructed did.
It was built quite minimally and arranging the rules so that the pressure was too high on the countries where these migrants first set foot.
I mean, we're free to move around, but we all have our own problems.
In the face of such a wave you can't do that, because some countries can't cope.
When there are these waves of emotion, politicians want to look like they're doing something, but in the long run it doesn't change much.
After the attacks in France we don't have much more draconian anti-terrorism legislation in the EU than we had last year.
There's a wave of public emotion building both ways.
And it's so unstable from one week to the next that you can't make decisions based on it.
We have a lot of talk, a lot of bellicose statements from politicians at home under pressure to be manly.
And then you have the dramatic case of the drowned child in Turkey and public opinion is stirred.
After the public emotion passes, we will return to the reasons why we created this space, this freedom of movement that is not only for people, but also for goods.
This is the real European single market.
And I don't think the Europeans are going to give up this principle of freedom of movement.
That there will be other rules is another.
Schengen is now like an animal that was created in another era and was not adapted to today's situation.
How has Romania played so far in this crisis?
It's like a small country that thinks if you pull the blinders over your eyes and plug your ears, the theme disappears.
Faced with the reality of migrant waves, you can choose to be part of the solution or say it's not your small country's problem.
That's what we did, it's a legitimate strategy, but then you can't ask to be treated like a seventh EU country.
You're not, you're not playing at the big country level.
Large countries come up with solutions for the whole EU, good or bad, we are not discussing their quality now.
Just like Poland did.
On the other hand, the effect of this crisis is that the Romanians' appetite for Schengen will decrease a lot.
President Iohannis says it's probably a good thing we're not in yet.
So we move from the desperation of entry to a more pragmatic position, but the objective remains.
There is of course a risk if Romania and Bulgaria join Schengen that migrants will see us as the alternative route.
Which is not a reason not to join Schengen, but to be more pragmatic.
Romania will be part of Schengen, and Schengen will exist, but transformed in the sense that the external borders will become a shared responsibility, there will be single rules for accepting migrants, single rules for deporting those who do not receive asylum, single rules for countries considered safe.
The Ukrainian president was saying that after Russia shifted its focus from Syria to Ukraine, no one died.
