What button will appear soon
Millions of Facebook users have grown accustomed to the "Like" button, and now the social network is preparing its opposite, the "Dislike" button.
On Tuesday, Mark Zuckerberg, the company's co-founder and chief executive, announced on his account that the button will be available soon, the New York Times reports on its blog.
Zuckerberg specified that the "Dislike" button would show a shade of what a user feels rather than a simple option.
However, his announcement raised concerns that Facebook could become a less friendly place.
Zuckerberg mentioned that he wants to avoid moments where someone posts on his account about an important life event, and someone else dislikes it.
Users of the network, which has grown to 1.5 billion active accounts, have long requested the ability to express their negative emotions or empathize with something sad.
Mark Zuckerberg also said that he's not really comfortable with people liking current events, like the refugee crisis, or the death of a family member.
"You may not feel comfortable liking that post", the Facebook representative pointed out.
The idea of a new Facebook button wasn't welcomed by everyone.
"There's already enough hate on Facebook and social media", Atiq Haneef from Afghanistan commented on the New York Times Facebook page, where the article was posted.
"I'm going to dislike the dislike button", he said.
Roger Anderson, a microbiologist from Atlanta, argued that there is nothing wrong with this button, encouraging people to have different opinions on Facebook.
Debra Aho Williamson, social media analyst at eMarketer, mentioned that it's hard to imagine that a single button can convey a complex range of negative emotions.
Moreover, she claims, the election campaign in America is approaching, and the "Dislike" button would create a total disaster.
