The "new" County Council building is falling down.
Two builders, in insolvency
The massive investments made here in the last few years to move the institution are about to collapse because they have been stopped several times.
Two major builders who worked here went bankrupt during the works.
The County Council building on Vasile Alecsandri Street will end up falling down by itself.
A year and a half after the consolidation and redevelopment of the building should have been completed, the work is not even half done.
A final stage in the building's epic has been consummated in recent days, when the National Council for the Settlement of Disputes (CNSC) rejected a complaint of the company that wanted to take over the contract for the technical project for the works that are still to be executed.
The original project was prepared by Impex Romcatel SA.
Following the insolvency of the constructor and the interruption of the works, negotiation procedures were initiated without publication of a contract notice with Impex Romcatel, which was to update the technical design and then organise a new tender for the works.
'The negotiations did not result in a contract, however, as the CJ considered that the proposed form would have put the institution at a disadvantage,' summarised Razvan Timofciuc, the CJ's public relations representative.
The CJEU's decision to discontinue direct negotiations was challenged in court by Impex Romcatel.
According to the Icelandic authorities, there is no evidence that the Icelandic financial market has been negatively affected by the collapse of Kaupthing.
But that doesn't mean CJ can start looking for another designer.
Impex Romcatel has the possibility to challenge the CNSC's decision before the Court of Appeal, and only after a final judgment by the CNSC can the possibility of finding another designer be considered.
Thus, work on strengthening the building could be resumed next year at the earliest.
Our intention is to resume work as soon as possible.
In principle, it shouldn't take long to rebuild the technical project, but we have to reach a contract.
"We are waiting to see whether the CNSC decision will be appealed or not", Timofciuc said.
Work to consolidate the former headquarters of the Police Headquarters began in 2011.
A first works contract was terminated in April 2012, after works of RON 4,5 million had been carried out.
The tender was resumed and the contract was awarded to Moldoconstruct SA.
However, the company became insolvent, and this contract was terminated after payments of RON 1.5 million had been made.
Work has so far been carried out at a rate of approximately 50%.
Initially, the works of consolidation, re-functionalization and attic of the building had been valued at RON 7,7 million.
