The coward, made a fool of by RATP controllers and a flyer.
The Misadventures of a Tourist
A family of tourists from Cluj came to Iasi to visit him, but the trip ended with a bitter promise.
After our experience, neither my wife nor I want to set foot in your town again.
Unwittingly, they encountered erroneous information in the leaflets, the insensitivity of the RAPT inspectors, and, bonus, a fine "according to the law".
The couple arrived in Iasi a few days ago, checked into a downtown hotel and asked for tourist brochures.
They also received a leaflet listing the RATP routes.
"Armed" with these maps, the couple visited Iasi.
But two days ago, out in Copou, they wanted to get to the Palace Mall.
Since there was no ticket machine at the station near Copou Park, they relied on the information printed on the flyer: that they could get a ticket by SMS.
No one told them that this service no longer exists.
Confident in the leaflet, they boarded a bus and tried to text the instructions on the leaflet.
Unfortunately for them, a team of RATP controllers appeared.
They said there hasn't been a service for two years and it's been announced in the press that it's been cancelled.
How would I know what was written in the local press, coming the night before I visited the city?
I talked to the controllers, explained the situation, they said they didn't care, it's none of their business.
The attitude was very defiant.
They said all they can do is give us one fine instead of two.
"I paid, I didn't want to ruin my visiting day standing at the gendarmerie and giving statements there!", says Ovidiu.
As a result, the family was fined because of the erroneous information in the leaflet and because the inspectors "applied the law to blood".
It's not fair, and I made a complaint to RATP Iasi to recover my money.
It's not about the money, I'm not exaggerated by many, but the point is that I felt cheated.
Bad luck for the rapists in Vaslui.
They had an accident and were remanded in custody
The trial of the seven rapists from Vaslui moved yesterday to the Court of Appeal of Iasi.
Magistrates in Iasi tried the first term of the trial in a closed session in which the seven young men accused of mocking an 18-year-old girl asked to be released.
Before the actual start of the hearing, one of the judges from Iasi to whom the case had been assigned, Viorel Munteanu, made a request to abstain, which was accepted by his colleagues in the court.
The magistrate worked until the summer of this year at the Vaslui Court, where he was the president of the Criminal Section, and it was he who, on 9 April, accepted an appeal by four of the defendants, ordering their placement under house arrest.
Currently, the case is being tried by a panel that includes magistrates Maricica Mititelu and Geta Sandu.
Earlier, Judge Dan Anton abstained from the case on the grounds that his daughter was in a common-law relationship with one of the rapists' lawyers.
The two judges ruled that the Vaslui rapists remain in custody.
The young people will remain in detention for at least another 30 days, when the judges will reconsider their release.
The next hearing will take place at the Iași Court of Appeal on 6 October.
Before reaching the Court of Appeal of Iasi, the van with which the rapists were transported from Vaslui was involved in an accident in the neighborhood of Păcurari, the car entering Iasi on the belt.
The Iveco van in which the seven rapists were travelling hit a Volkswagen car which had left Canta Street and the driver tried to turn left.
The van was coming from the end of Pacurari.
The car entered Iasi through here because the employees of the Penitentiary Administration preferred the route from Vaslui to Iasi via Grajduri, then on the ring road.
They thus shortened the trip by several miles.
Immediately after impact, the detainee escort called for another transport to pick up the prisoners.
Shortly after, a car from the Iași Maximum Security Prison was sent to the scene of the accident, which picked up the seven inmates and transported them to the Court of Appeal.
As a result of the accident, none of those arrested were injured.
To transfer them to the other van, the guards surrounded the rear of the cars and the detainees sped out, two by two.
"The incident was not reported to the police because the drivers of the two vehicles agreed on the damages to be paid", said Chief Commissioner Mădălin Țăranu of the IPJ.
The Great Migrations
Romania is not and will not be prepared for what is coming.
What about Europe?
I say it from the beginning, clearly and loudly: the almost 7000 refugees that Romania should and must naturalize represent, in itself, an insignificant but huge number compared to the capacity of the Romanian state to manage such a project.
For Romania, even the voluntary quota proposed by Bucharest, amounting to about 1500 people, far exceeds our good intentions of solidarity with the European Union expressed in recent months.
Certainly, if those migrants do accept to settle in our localities, the chances of quickly integrating them into Romanian society are extremely low.
I'm sure they'll be the first to lose their patience.
Parasitized by interlopers and paralyzed by a venal political class, the Romanian state proves impotent in all areas.
The failure to integrate Gypsies is just one banal example.
In addition, governments of all stripes have been unable to absorb European funds, build modern roads, kindergartens or schools, provide decent health care, clean up the streets, create decently paid jobs or keep their own young generation at home.
Why would refugees settle in another country they're fleeing?
But what is especially puzzling is the hypocrisy with which such a crisis is handled.
First, there is the bellicose hypocrisy of the powerful EU states, which are extremely generous when it comes to sharing the burdens of smaller countries.
Then comes the fearful hypocrisy of Romanians who, although they have millions of relatives scattered all over the world, still do not accept the other - of another language, another religion, another blood.
Probably afraid someone will steal his national essence.
Finally, there is the hypocrisy of many migrants who, while invoking only the horrors of war as a reason for leaving, accept no other destination for the exodus than Germany or the Nordic countries.
Now, not all refugees are Syrians, and there is no war in Pakistan.
Also, the simplistic way in which the crisis is analyzed can only be ridiculed.
The causes must be addressed, some argue, and, strictly on the political correctness card, they call for peace and investment in migrants' home countries.
But in Romania there is peace and even some foreign capital enters the national economy from time to time - but this does not prevent tens of thousands of Romanians from leaving their country every year.
Why is he leaving?
In this crisis, the European Union has revealed itself to us as an anchored, divided and outdated construction.
We lamented the fact that Romania is not capable of inventing a country project, but here the EU has no plan for the future.
And improvising and threatening doesn't help.
So what good is the EU if the only advantage Romanians enjoy - the right to free movement - could be jeopardised by waves of refugees streaming across borders?
At some point, the war in Syria will end.
But not the migrant crisis.
Over the coming decades, overpopulation, poverty, climate change, resource depletion and so on will drive millions of desperate migrants from Asia and especially Africa to seek a better life.
With such politicians, Romania is not and will never be prepared for what is to come.
