EXCLUSIVE: A meeting that will break your heart.
At 20, she received a courageous gift: biological parents.
Lost in the hospital in unclear circumstances, in the dark of the 90s, when she was only two months old, small, sickly and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family in Italy, in the same years when adoption was vaguely regulated, a young girl from Iasi, now a blonde and beautiful girl, was reunited the day before yesterday in Iasi with her biological parents from a village in the county, after almost two decades in which no one knew anything about the others.
Crina is about to turn 20 years old, and her adoptive parents in Palermo have decided to give their beloved daughter a surprising and brave gift: a visit to Romania, to Iasi, to learn about her unclear past.
"Ziarul de Iași", which witnessed the efforts to search for the family of origin after some extremely vague clues, witnessed these meetings that practically break your heart.
The reporters' accounts, the emotions of the moment, the statements of those involved, their reactions are truly moving and overwhelming.
Crina's story begins 20 years ago in the town of Ruginoasa, Iasi, when she was only two months old.
Then, because of a health problem, the girl had to be hospitalized in the city.
My parents quarreled, and my mother left home.
He decided to keep the girl and send me away.
He stopped the girl, and I haven't heard from her since.
"By the time I found out that she was in the hospital, it was too late", recalls Alina, the girl's grieving mother.
Crina was admitted with her grandmother to the municipal hospital in Pașcani, and the girl's father, Costică Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman county.
Their lives were about to end forever.
They never found Crina at the hospital.
After Crina's admission, her father went to work in another locality, and returned after six months.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the hospital in Iasi, and the father, when he returned, did not find her.
It must have been almost nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
"She must have thought she was abandoned", says a granddaughter of the family.
Due to financial problems, the grandmother could not come with Crina to Iasi, and the girl remained in the care of doctors.
Because no one was interested in the fate of the child in all this time, she was taken over by the General Directorate of Social Assistance and Child Protection of Iasi, which then gave her to the care of the Placement Center in Bucium.
Those were years when abandonment and adoption were more loosely regulated than today in Romania.
At the Bucium Center she was found by the Italian Salvadore and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but could not.
They immediately fell in love with the blonde Crina, and after some time she would move permanently with them to Italy.
She was almost two years old by the time the adoption was finalized.
When I saw Crina, I felt like she was our daughter.
"It's as if my wife gave birth to her", smiles Salvadore, her adoptive father, as he takes her fragile hand in his.
In the country, Crinia's parents, Alina and Costica, continued the search separately, each where they could.
The father asked the authorities in Ruginoasa, but received no answer where his child could be.
The police then told her that she might be dead, but in Iasi the parents found out what really happened to their daughter.
When I looked for her here, they told me at the court that she had gone to Italy, to Palermo.
And the conditions to look for her I never had.
We prayed to God that he was okay.
I've thought about it all these years, but there's been no way to walk around and find it.
"It's hard", says Crina's biological mother with tears in her eyes.
But even after all these years, the parents in Ruginoasa have not been forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past linked her to Romania.
I was little when I found out.
I think I was five or six.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
"I wanted to get to know my Romanian parents", says a delighted Crina.
And her dream was about to come true.
In March of this year, Chief Commissioner Romică Ichim, director of the Regional Center for Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling in Iași, was contacted by an acquaintance in Italy who explained Salvadore's desire to find Crina's biological family.
And the searches started with just one name.
Following a request from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
I only got one name, Balkan Costica, then the town, Ruginoasa.
Soon I had an activity with the town hall there, and I could ask if there by locality the name received.
That's when they gave me some leads, only the person they found wasn't the person they were looking for.
"It took us about a month to finally find the girl's biological father", explains Chief Commissioner Romică Ichim.
Altogether, it took the authorities more than three months to find Costică and Alina, especially since they lived in different towns.
We started the process around March, and by June-July we had completed the identification of the biological parents and the discussions.
"We then arranged for a first meeting to be held in September", added Romică Ichim.
Last weekend, Alina and Costica saw their lost daughter for the first time in the halls of the hospital in Iasi, 20 years ago.
The emotional father could hardly hold back his tears, and his hands were trembling uncontrollably.
He barely exchanges a few words with anyone.
The week before the meeting, he could barely sleep.
He was all excited, trembling.
"To see your child after so many years is something", says a granddaughter, who also came with Costica from Ruginoasa.
Carina's reunion with her biological mother and brother
In discussions with his daughter, who is about to study at a prestigious university in Italy, Costica Balcan told her, among other things, that if she ever wanted to return to his village, she should come quietly: he could give her some sheep, goats, so that she could find a village boy and start a household.
The mother is also emotional, crying, and finds it hard to believe that this could happen to her.
I'm really excited.
I never thought something like this could happen.
I've seen cases like this on TV, I've been thinking about it all these years, I've been hoping, but I never thought I could be like that.
There are very big emotions.
If only he could forgive me.
I hope we can visit in the future.
"I hope we can keep in touch", says Crinia's mother, Alina, with tears welling up in her eyes.
In it she also hides her tears of happiness, because soon she will see her daughter after so much bitter time.
On the other hand, Crina, who will turn 20 in just a few days this month, tries to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn't know what to expect, but she has a vague idea about her biological parents.
She thinks they're young, but now before the meeting she's trying to gather her thoughts, because she has a lot to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two moms and two dads.
But my parents are ultimately the ones who raised me.
It will be a beautiful meeting, a wonderful experience.
"I hope to have a good memory with them, because now there is so much to talk about", says Carina.
First family reunion in Iași
In Union Square, under the early autumn sky, the Ruginoasa family reunites their destiny with their Palermo daughter.
Crina is now 20 years old, finishing high school, following the Italian school model, but she can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
They are no longer divided by borders or countries, but only by a barrier: that of language.
Over which, with the help of a translator, an Italian restaurant owner in the center of Iasi, they passed easily.
Those who made this meeting possible say that it is the first event of its kind ever, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do it again.
It's the first event of its kind organized, of such an emotional charge, and I'm glad it's a success.
We, at the Centre, have different activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with people who use, people who are addicted to drugs.
But we're trying to give something back to society.
"If I'm asked again for an event like this, I'll do it with great pleasure", says Romică Ichim, director of the Regional Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counselling Centre in Iași, with a smile.
Behind him, the Balkan family, with Crina in the middle, walk away talking.
They're understandable: they have a lot to say to each other.
