Anton invoked the fact that one of the defendants' attorneys, attorney Bogdan Luca, is the common-law husband of his daughter, attorney Dana Anton.
Luca defends Silviu Ovidiu Burada, who received the highest sentence in this case.
How the Judges Reasoned
At the end of last week, the magistrate of the Vaslui Court who sentenced the seven young people gave reasons for the sentence.
In his reasoning, the judge speaks of the defiant reaction of the defendants, but also of those who supported them, stating that such attitudes create a strong sense of indignation among the public.
"The court finds that after the placement under the preventive measure of judicial control, a measure restricting freedom but not depriving of liberty, under the impact of the attitude of the defendants, their families and local supporters, a strong sense of indignation was felt at the local and national community level about the fact that persons accused of serious offences are tried under a less restrictive measure, "says the reasoning of the Vaslui Court.
The magistrates also dismantled the main defense of the seven defendants who during the trial invoked the fact that the girl they raped would not be a "church door".
'The court emphasises that the moral quality of the injured person is irrelevant, an aspect that the defendants have sought to highlight through the defenses they have formulated, since the physical and sexual freedom of a person cannot be violated under any pretext,' the reasoning also states.
Corbyn, Brexit and the future of Europe
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in recent decades cannot continue in the coming years.
Until Saturday probably few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn is.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the Labour Party in Britain, many are wondering to what extent we can affect the election of a politician who, after all, is not in a decision-making position.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical left-wing Labour leader since the war.
An avowed Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once called on then-Prime Minister Tony Blair to remove the royal family from Buckingham Palace), fiercely anti-American and a supporter of Vladimir Putin (he has been regularly invited to comment on political events by the Russia Today television channel), and the terrorist movements Hezbollah and Hamas, he wants Britain to give up its nuclear weapons and leave NATO and the EU.
For Corbyn, who at the time regarded the killing of Osama bin Laden as a tragedy, ISIS is almost preferable to the United States.
Like all populist demagogues, Corbyn of course has anti-austerity silver bullets.
The kind of things that Tsipras was saying and promising in Greece until he faced the real world and the economic realities.
The economic programme of the new Labour leader envisages, among other things, massive renationalisations and the printing of money as a solution for financing development projects and covering very generous social benefits.
Of course, some might wonder why the printing money solution is not universally adopted across the globe, we would then have a general global prosperity!
Sure, we can tax the bankers to the bone, make them some kind of official enemy of the left, but as we've seen so many times in the past, not just in the former communist states or in Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of Mitterrand and Hollande.
The additional sums are quickly swallowed up by the generous, empty promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher rightly pointed out, 'the problem with socialism is that eventually you run out of other people's money'.
Few give Jeremy Corbyn a realistic chance of ever becoming Prime Minister.
In the early 1980s another radical left leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in his beliefs as the new party leader anyway, failed miserably in the elections.
And there was still in Britain a working class, in the classical sense of the word, relatively substantial and structured.
And the unions were considerably more influential than they are now.
In the context of the new industrial landscape, where services dominate the workforce and extensive automation has left industry in massive need of highly skilled labour, Corbyn's rhetoric has limited appeal.
But even in opposition, he can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes that Corbyn's election increases the chances of Brexit, the United Kingdom's exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country's membership of the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that has imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with the radical right's anti-immigration rhetoric and look at the refugee crisis that is shaking the foundations of the EU, you get an explosive mix.
And not just for Britain.
But if the British decide, in a referendum to be held by 2017, to leave the Union, the loss of symbolic capital for the entire European project and the deep rifts created within it by the Euro crisis and now by the refugee crisis, between North and South, between East and West, leaves room for the most worrying scenarios.
This was all the more so as, for a number of Member States, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which Berlin was increasingly becoming the dominant player).
It's true, Britain's business community, the City, are strong advocates of remaining in the EU.
But today's Europe is not the Europe of the past.
There's a lot of resentment, and it's growing in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, we had a sample of it just recently in Jean-Claude Juncker's speech, tends more and more to make major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of member states by consulting only a few European powers, mainly Germany.
And this is happening at a time when electoral support for anti-establishment, anti-immigration parties that are also Eurosceptic is rising dramatically across the continent.
In other words, the negatively charged emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever in the past.
Hence the conclusion reached by the Financial Times when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation of the national interest.
If voters make the cerebral decision, then Britain will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn's victory reminds us of the power of emotion in politics today.
Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as is expected, we will see a more pronounced integration of the Eurozone, which will push most of the states in the region to the periphery of interest and decision-making in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States feed their populist rhetoric from the accumulated frustrations in Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed in recent decades, the generous social benefits, cannot continue in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, Eurozone - immigration, both caused by hasty decisions that took into account only the integrationist political ambitions, not the capacity and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and may seriously affect the situation of Romania.
And it's hard to rule anything out in terms of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to deal with such complicated situations.
Constantine Brancusi, the peasant god.
Rockefeller: "How can I help you?"
Brancusi: "Go and sweep the workshop!"
The great sculptor had a big dream: to be somebody, to become famous, to be heard all over the world.
But behind his fame lies something almost forgotten today, when millions of success stories, recipes for success in life, are delivered to us.
And that something has a name.
It's called hard work.
What to write about Constantin Brancusi?
What else is there to say, really?
His face appeared on the bills.
And recently, a well-known bank in Romania hired an actor to play him in a commercial.
Brancusi produces and delivers money almost 60 years after he is no longer with us.
In Romania, there are hundreds of streets and boulevards named after him.
By the way, even the author of this text lives on one of these streets.
And when she goes outside with her cub, she hears the following instructions: "We're going to the park, to Brancusi's".
The country is littered with his statues.
There are few Romanian personalities whose works are known by so many people, from children to the elderly.
Brancusi's ability to infiltrate is enormous.
Even the communists failed to eradicate it from the memory and culture of Romania.
His quotes are now all over the internet, receiving hundreds of thousands of likes and shares.
And then, again, what would there be to say, to write about this man?
Seen from the pile of books and articles that attempt to reconstruct his fate, Brancusi's life seems almost fantastic, totally improbable.
You know, there are those people who tell you that unless you're lucky enough to be born in a big city and into a moderately wealthy family, your chances of success in life are pretty much nil.
Brancusi's life is the perfect counterexample.
And maybe here would be a key.
Perhaps this is where the following text should begin.
With a sentence, however detestable they are.
Forget about the crappy success stories that are delivered to you every day in newspapers and on television.
Look closely at this man's face.
Do you want to know how he made it in life, how, today, the whole world heard about him?
It's as simple as that.
He's worked his whole life to be somebody.
That's what he did.
Constantin Brâncuși was born on 19 February 1876 in Hobița, a small village in the commune of Peștișani, Gorj County, at the foot of the Carpathians.
He is the fifth child of Maria and Radu Nicolae Brancusi.
Although he came from a wealthy peasant family, Brancusi led a modest life, but one from which he would pick up the landmarks that would guide his later artistic vision.
Recalling his childhood and the places where he grew up, the artist would confess in a meeting with Petre Țuțea in Paris in 1933: "At that time life was beautiful and harmonious".
For millennia, humans have happily lived a patriarchal life.
Everything went smoothly from one season to the next.
And you know why things changed?
The civilization of the great city has come down to us.
Brancusi's childhood was far from idyllic.
One of the moments spent in these early years is extremely suggestive of the combination of purity and violence that characterized the future sculptor's years spent in his native village.
The moment is reproduced in the work "Brâncuși.
In 1879, Constantin Brancusi was 3 years old.
In the autumn of that year, when the cottage cheese was being made "in the cauldron", watching those who tasted the liquid to see if the process was going well, Brancusi catches a moment of general inattention.
He fills the cups of his hands with brandy and drinks without stopping.
He falls asleep almost instantly.
It takes the first humans a few minutes to notice.
The mother panics, then hysterics, thinking her son is dead.
Towards evening, when the father, Radu, returns from the vineyard accompanied by lutenists, he sees from afar the desperate signs of those waiting for him with bated breath.
The party quickly turns to mourning.
Father's already thinking about the funeral.
However, someone finds it good to call Baba Brandușa, doctor and servant of the Brancusi.
The midwife checks the baby's breathing, then places horse manure, collected from the surrounding area, under the baby's nose.
The child sneezes loudly.
People are applauding.
While the boy is allowed to sleep off his joy drunkenness, the lute party continues with even more vigor.
The next day, father and son meet by the orchard.
Radu Brancusi has Constantine gather some sticks and bring them to him.
The father puts his child upside down and, with the sticks brought by the boy, beats him to remember.
And as he feels the sting of the blows, little Brancusi has the revelation that the world can also be seen from another perspective and that things around him can appear upside down.
Especially the position of the sun, different from the well-known one, makes him wonder, as he would recognize in his old age, if the star itself did not participate in his disturbance.
Was the sun as troubled by what had happened to him as his father had been?
